Container base images are a foundational component of application security, performance, and operational efficiency. Within JPMC, the recommended base images for secure application delivery are built on Red Hat Universal Base Image (UBI).
This provides application teams with an opportunity not only to migrate to RHEL 9, but also to adopt UBI9 Minimal and UBI9 Micro base images — one of the most effective ways to implement a Secure-by-Design strategy.
These compact base images significantly reduce the vulnerability footprint, while also reducing image size and improving container startup performance.
Compared to the legacy Standard image formulation, UBI9 Minimal and Micro images dramatically reduce the number of installed packages and therefore reduce the number of potential vulnerabilities.
If you are planning to upgrade to RHEL UBI9, this article outlines how to get the greatest benefit from that transition. Even teams already using UBI9 Standard images can realise significant security and operational improvements by switching to Minimal or Micro variants.
Why the Shift Matters: Eliminating “Vulnerability Debt”
Quote: Every unnecessary package removed from a base image removes a potential vulnerability before it ever reaches production.
Traditional Standard base images mirror the historical approach of installing applications on full operating systems running on physical servers.
As a result, Standard UBI images often include more than 180 packages, many of which are unnecessary for containerised workloads.
Every additional package introduces potential:
	•	attack surface
	•	vulnerability exposure
	•	operational maintenance overhead
Utilities such as shells, package managers, and other OS components that are rarely needed in runtime containers may still appear in VSaaS (Vulnerability Scanning as a Service) vulnerability scans and require remediation.
Reducing the number of packages helps eliminate this “vulnerability debt” at its source and aligns container builds with our Secure-by-Design engineering strategy.


