JPMC Best Practices for Container Excellence


Once migrated, following container best practices ensures images remain secure and efficient.
Automate with Renovate:
Renovate automatically creates pull requests when updated and more secure base image tags become available. Never use the :latest tag. Use version tags (e.g. 1.2.3) or immutable SHA digests (image@sha256:...).

Build Immutable Containers
All application binaries and dependencies should be included during the image build process.
Downloading binaries at runtime is a critical anti-pattern because it:
	•	bypasses VSaaS scanning
	•	introduces supply chain risks
	•	reduces deployment reproducibility

Rebuild Images Regularly
Even if your application code does not change, the security landscape evolves continuously. Container images should therefore be rebuilt periodically to ensure:
	•	Updated base image patches are incorporated
	•	New security fixes and vulnerability remediations are included
	•	Container registry retention policies (e.g., Artifactory) do not impact image availability for deployments
Regular rebuilds help ensure container workloads remain secure, compliant, and reliable over time.
Keep Container Images as Small as Possible
Smaller container images deploy faster and inherently reduce the attack surface by limiting the number of installed components. Fewer components also reduce the likelihood of GEM, REC, and Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVEs) appearing in the image lifecycle.
